{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"79923b08-b7e3-41b9-a3d2-e1a2c18a4ab8","content":"In .NET MAUI, those methods moved from `Application` to `Window`. You have two options:\n\n**Option 1 â€” Subscribe to Window events in `App.xaml.cs`:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 â€” Subclass `Window`:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen return `new MyWindow(new AppShell())` from `CreateWindow`.\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` / `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` / `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` / `OnResumed()` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ee38d66c-02c2-48a3-9260-cb7c22f9478a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. The `Application` class no longer has those virtual methods. Instead, you override `CreateWindow()` and subscribe to window events, or use platform-specific lifecycle events via the builder.\n\n\nMore specifically, you can override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` directly on the `Window` class, subscribe to window events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying`, or configure platform-specific lifecycle events through `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`. The most straightforward migration is to override `CreateWindow()` in your `App` class and return a custom `Window` subclass where you can handle these lifecycle events.","outputTokens":838,"requestId":"1018:163FFF:1528694:17C4F15:69FD34A1"},"id":"f8f7d118-04e4-4885-b6f0-265a2bd34351","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:56:16.079Z","parentId":"6700a948-f817-4efe-bae8-90c83169653e"}
